  "prompt": "Which mathematician solved the magic square problem?",
  "response": "The concept of magic squares has been known and explored by various mathematicians throughout history rather than being \"solved\" by a single individual. \n\nMagic squares, grids where the sums of numbers in each row, column, and diagonal are equal, have been studied since ancient times. Early examples are found in Chinese texts like the \"Lo Shu Square,\" dating back to around 2200 BCE. In medieval Islam, Abu'l Wafa and Al-Buni made significant contributions to the study of magic squares.\n\nDuring the Renaissance, European mathematicians like Leonhard Euler expanded on these ideas, creating methods for constructing magic squares of different orders. However, no single mathematician is credited with \"solving\" magic squares, as the study of magic squares encompasses a broad range of mathematical insights and methods developed over centuries.",
